sim_bg = makedist('Poisson','lambda',2000);
total_event = 2000+50;
pb = 1-cdf(sim_bg,total_event)
pb = 0.1296
significant = norminv(1-pb)
significant = 1.1282
cal_significant = 50/sqrt(2000)
cal_significant = 1.1180
%significant means how far the probability of a event to the expect value
%comparing by std of expect distribution. We know the difference between
%observation and background caused by signal, and the std of Poisson
%distribution is sqrt of lambda. Therefore, we can calculate how far
%observation will away to background expect value by [N(signal)/std of
%expect distribution]. It is the same we calculate probability of
%obsevation by background distribution and find the distance between its
%sigma value and mean of Normal std distribution.
%Problem 2
%Based on the graph, I decide to choose 130 as mean point(highest
%probability point)
h_mass_cut = 0;
for i = 1:length(higgs_mass)
if higgs_mass(i)>=120 & higgs_mass(i)<=140
h_mass_cut = [h_mass_cut;higgs_mass(i)];
end
end
h_mass_cut = h_mass_cut(2:end,:);
q_mass_cut = 0;
for i = 1:length(qcd_mass)
if qcd_mass(i)>=120 & qcd_mass(i)<=140
q_mass_cut = [q_mass_cut;qcd_mass(i)];
end
end
q_mass_cut = q_mass_cut(2:end,:);
figure()
histogram(h_mass_cut)
hold on
histogram(q_mass_cut)
title({'Optimal mass cuts 120-140','Significant = ',num2str(length(h_mass_cut)/sqrt(length(q_mass_cut)))})
